Problem-Oriented Development is an emerging paradigm of computing that emphasises problems (as opposed to requirements) as the primary subject of scrutiny by software engineers. As such, Problem-Oriented Development is concerned with:
BULLET::::- Investigating the structure of organisational problems as addressed by Software Engineering;
BULLET::::- Providing formalisms for modelling and representing problems;
BULLET::::- Providing guidance and frameworks for problem analysis and decomposition;
BULLET::::- Defining techniques for formally justifying solutions (e.g. by associating problem components with solution components);
BULLET::::- Supporting knowledge reuse during problem analysis (e.g. through problem patterns).
